T1  - Effects of Corporate Sponsorship and Departmental Power on Career Tournaments
AU  - Sheridan, John E.
AU  - Slocum, John W.
AU  - Buda, Richard
AU  - Thompson, Richard C.
Y1  - 1990/09/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256582
DO  - 10.5465/256582
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 578
EP  - 602
VL  - 33
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study addressed the internal career mobility over a ten-year period of 338 managers employed by a single firm. We found that how managers started their careers in the company and the power of the department in which they started strongly influenced rates of job promotion, transfer, and salary progression. The implications for ?career tournament? processes are discussed.
AB  - This study addressed the internal career mobility over a ten-year period of 338 managers employed by a single firm. We found that how managers started their careers in the company and the power of the department in which they started strongly influenced rates of job promotion, transfer, and salary progression. The implications for ?career tournament? processes are discussed.
